    Your Allocation Style is determined based on the rounded percentage of equity holdings in your selected accounts as follows:

    • if equity % is less than or equal to 10%, then Short Term;
    • if equity % is between 11% - 24%, then Conservative;
    • if equity % is between 25% - 34%, then Moderate With Income;
    • if equity % is between 35% - 44%, then Moderate;
    • if equity % is between 45% - 54%, then Balanced;
    • if equity % is between 55% - 64%, then Growth With Income;
    • if equity % is between 65% - 78%, then Growth;
    • if equity % is between 79% - 92%, then Aggressive Growth;
    • if equity % is greater than or equal to 93% then Most Aggressive;

    Price improvement details provided for domestic stock and single leg option orders entered during market hours after the primary opening, provided there is a National Best Bid and Offer (NBBO) at the time the order is placed. Price improvement details are provided for informational purposes only and are not used for regulatory reporting purposes.

    Buy market orders with a weighted average execution price below the National Best Offer (NBO) are considered price improved. Price improvement for buy market orders is calculated by subtracting the weighted average execution price from the NBO, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on buy limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the NBO minus the execution price and the limit price minus the execution price. Sell market orders with a weighted average execution price above the National Best Bid (NBB) are considered price improved. Price improvement for sell market orders is calculated by subtracting the NBB from the weighted average execution price, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on sell limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the execution price minus the NBB and the execution price minus the limit price.

    Prior to December 7, 2015, price improvement for limit orders (buy and sell) was calculated using the methodology for price improvement on market orders described above.

    For buys and sells, price improvement is displayed per execution and per order, only when an order has been net price improved. Price improvements at the execution and individual order level are rounded down to the nearest penny.

    Price improvement data is not provided for not held orders, all or none orders, sell short orders, and orders placed outside of standard market hours.

    Some orders may not receive any price improvement. Fast market conditions and large order sizes relative to the bid or ask size may result in shares executing at or outside the NBBO. To learn more about our commitment to execution quality, click here.

    To learn more about average price trade reporting, including how to enroll or unenroll, click here.

    If you have entered an order with specific share information and you would like to change the order, please see Viewing and Changing Specific Shares in Help for special instructions. If you are attempting to change your order quantity, you must follow these special instructions; otherwise, the replacement order will not have specific share information.
    Note: Cost information on retirement accounts is not provided for tax reporting purposes. There is no tax related impact for retirement accounts by specifying shares. This information is provided to retirement accounts for performance tracking only.

    Orders placed using Electronic Communication Network (ECN) are automatically canceled if they are not filled by the end of the trading session. The Premarket session ends at 9:28 a.m. Eastern Time unless trading is halted prior to 9:28 a.m. Eastern Time. The After Hours session ends at 8 p.m. Eastern Time unless trading is halted prior to 8 p.m. Eastern Time.

    Use the market session and order confirmation number to identify ECN orders in a list of orders.

    For international orders, Fidelity does not participate in the extended hours trading sessions. Any international order entered outside of regular Exchange hours for that country will be placed for the next business day. See International Market Hours table for specific country trading hours.

    Price improvement details provided for domestic stock and single leg option orders entered during market hours after the primary opening, provided there is a National Best Bid and Offer (NBBO) at the time the order is placed. Price improvement details are provided for informational purposes only and are not used for regulatory reporting purposes.

    Buy market orders with a weighted average execution price below the National Best Offer (NBO) are considered price improved. Price improvement for buy market orders is calculated by subtracting the weighted average execution price from the NBO, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on buy limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the NBO minus the execution price and the limit price minus the execution price. Sell market orders with a weighted average execution price above the National Best Bid (NBB) are considered price improved. Price improvement for sell market orders is calculated by subtracting the NBB from the weighted average execution price, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on sell limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the execution price minus the NBB and the execution price minus the limit price.

    Prior to December 7, 2015, price improvement for limit orders (buy and sell) was calculated using the methodology for price improvement on market orders described above.

    Some orders may not receive any price improvement. Fast market conditions and large order sizes relative to the bid or ask size may result in shares executing at or outside the NBBO. To learn more about our commitment to execution quality, click here.

    Total Price Improvement reflects the sum of net price improvements on eligible orders executed within the stated timeframe. Orders with a weighted average execution price above the ask (for buys) or below the bid (for sells) are not factored into the Total Price Improvement figures. See Trading FAQs  for more information.

    Today's Markets provides access to quotes, delayed by 10 minutes, for select front-month futures contracts. The front-month contract will automatically roll to the next contract month upon expiration, when it has an open interest more than twice the current month, or its trading volume is larger.

Your results may vary with each use and over time.

    Retirement Analysis, including the Retirement Preparedness Measure (RPM), is based on information you provided and certain assumptions, including market performance assumptions based on hypothetical scenarios using historical index data. Numerous factors make the calculations uncertain, such as the use of assumptions about historical returns and inflation, as well as the data you have provided. Fund fees and other expenses will generally reduce your actual investment returns and are generally not reflected in the hypothetical projections.

    The information contained in the CSV version of your tax forms is general in nature, and is provided for informational purposes only. You should use the official tax forms that Fidelity sends by mail for purposes of tax return preparation.     Unless otherwise specified, NFS determines cost basis at the time of sale based on the average cost method for open-end mutual funds and based on the first-in, first-out (FIFO) method for all other securities.

    A covered tax lot indicates that Fidelity will include cost basis and holding period information on the annual 1099-B for the year the tax lot is closed. Consult your tax advisor for further information.

    Performance data shown represents past performance and is no guarantee of future results. Investment return and principal value will fluctuate, so investors may have a gain or loss when shares are sold. Current performance may be higher or lower than what is quoted, and investors should visit Fidelity.com/performance for most recent month-end performance.
